1. File System Navigation
Command	Description
pwd	Print current directory
ls	List files
ls -la	List all files with permissions
cd <dir>	Change directory
cd ..	Move one directory back
clear	Clear terminal screen

2. File & Directory Management
Command	Description
mkdir <folder>	Create new folder
rmdir <folder>	Remove empty folder
rm <file>	Delete file
rm -r <folder>	Delete folder recursively
cp <src> <dest>	Copy file
mv <src> <dest>	Move or rename file
touch <file>	Create empty file

3. File Permissions
Command	Description
chmod 777 <file>	Give full permissions
chmod +x <file>	Make file executable
chown user:group <file>	Change file ownership
ls -l	View file permissions

Permission Format:

r = read
w = write
x = execute

4. Package Management (Debian/Kali)
Command	Description
sudo apt update	Update package list
sudo apt upgrade	Upgrade packages
sudo apt install <pkg>	Install package
sudo apt remove <pkg>	Remove package
dpkg -i <file.deb>	Install .deb file

5. Networking Commands
Command	Description
ifconfig	Show IP address
ip a	Show network interfaces
ping <IP>	Test connectivity
netstat -tulnp	Show open ports
ss -tuln	List listening ports
traceroute <IP>	Trace packet route

6. Basic Scanning & Enumeration
Command	Description
nmap <IP>	Basic scan
nmap -sS <IP>	SYN scan
nmap -sV <IP>	Service version detection
whoami	Current user
id	User ID info

7. Process Management
Command	Description
ps	Show running processes
ps aux	Detailed process list
top	Real-time process monitor
kill <PID>	Kill process
kill -9 <PID>	Force kill

8. OpenSSL (Cryptography Basics)

Encrypt File:

openssl enc -aes-256-cbc -salt -in file.txt -out encrypted.txt

Decrypt File:

openssl enc -aes-256-cbc -d -in encrypted.txt -out decrypted.txt

Hash File:

sha256sum file.txt
md5sum file.txt

9. Useful Shortcuts
Shortcut	Action
Ctrl + C	Stop running command
Ctrl + Z	Pause process
Tab	Auto-complete
history	Show command history

10. Important Directories
Directory	Purpose
/home	User files
/etc	Configuration files
/var	Logs
/bin	System binaries
/root	Root user home
